Capstone project

The Coursera Data Science Specialization Capstone project from Johns Hopkins University (JHU) allows students to create a usable public data product that can show their skills to potential employers. Projects are drawn from real-world problems and are conducted with industry, government, and academic partners. For this iteration of the class, JHU is partnering with SwiftKey (http://swiftkey.com/en/) to apply data science in the area of natural language processing.

The objective of this project was to build a working predictive text model. The data used in the model came from a corpus called HC Corpora (www.corpora.heliohost.org). A corpus is body of text, usually containing a large number of sentences.

Milestone report

This milestone report explains the exploratory data analysis and goals for the eventual text prediction app and algorithm. This report explains the major feature of the data and briefly summarizes the plans for creating the prediction algorithm and Shiny app.

The Data

The data includes sample from three text sources; blogs, news and twitter. The data is available at [“https://d396qusza40orc.cloudfront.net/dsscapstone/dataset/Coursera-SwiftKey.zip”]. List of bad words were downloaded from [“http://www.bannedwordlist.com/lists/swearWords.txt”].

Summary of data is described below:

Exploratory Data Analysis

Sampling the data

In order do to exploratory data analysis, we begin by taking 3.5% sample from all sources (news, blogs and twitter), removing non-ASCII characters and saving it.

set.seed(6931)
sample_all <- c(sample_text(blogs.txt),sample_text(news.txt), sample_text(twitter.txt))
sample_all <- iconv(sample_all, "latin1", "ASCII", sub = "")
dest_file<-"./data/sample/all_sample.txt"
sample_save(sample_all,dest_file)

Cleaning and preprocessing

In order preprocess and clean data, we first create a corpus object.

data.en_US.sample <- VCorpus(DirSource(directory = "./data/sample/", encoding = "UTF-8"))

Then we will clean the data by:

  1. Converting to lower case
  2. Removing url addresses
  3. Cleaning up the tweets (twitter accounts, RT & via)
  4. Removing numbers
  5. Removing punctuation
  6. Removing profanity
  7. Removing stopwords
  8. Removing extra white space

The clean data sample is saved as an RDS file.

After that we will tokenize the data using into unigrams, bigrams and trigrams using the RWeka package.
